ODE XVIII.

In this ode Horace inveighs against luxury and extravagance as the prevailing vices of the age. The ode may be considered as consisting of three parts. In the first, the poet exposes the licentious enormities of the age 3 in the second, he shows their causes3 and in the third, points out their proper reme- dies. .

24. Et peccare : there were four things which seemed to have influence in securing the happiness of marriage among the Scythians3 a virtuous education, an attachment of wives to their husbands, their horror of conjugal infidelity, and the severity of their laws in punishing that crime with death.
